<h4><a href="http://alexschroeder.ch/wiki/2014-01-31_Virtual_Photography">Virtual Photography</a></h4>
<div class="entry">
<div class="content">
<p>I just stumbled over <a class="url http outside" href="http://evetravel.wordpress.com/">EVE Travel</a>, with pictures and stories from the <a class="near" title="Wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EVE_Online">EVE Online</a> world. What a wall of text. But the pictures! Never having played EVE, I keep getting reminded of my days as a kid playing <a class="near" title="Wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wing_Commander_(video_game)">Wing Commander</a> 1 &amp; 2 on a computer that would be unfit to be my phone&#x2019;s audio processor, I guess. I&#x2019;ve seen blogs with photographs of virtual worlds before, and it just keeps amazing me. How far we have come!</p><p>Some <a class="url http outside" href="http://virtualgeographic.tumblr.com/search/skyrim">black and white images</a> from <a class="near" title="Wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sykrim">Sykrim</a>, for example. Or hipster <a class="url http outside" href="http://virtualgeographic.tumblr.com/search/mirror%27s+edge">Instagram pictures</a> from <a class="near" title="Wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirror's_Edge">Mirror's Edge</a>.</p><p>Tags: <a class="outside tag" title="Tag" rel="tag" href="http://alexschroeder.ch/wiki?action=tag;id=Games">Games</a> <a class="feed tag" title="Feed for this tag" rel="feed" href="http://alexschroeder.ch/wiki/feed/full/Games"><img src="http://alexschroeder.ch/pics/rss.png" alt="RSS" /></a></p></div>







