▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓░░░░░░░▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓
▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓░░░▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓
▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓
▓▓▓▓▓░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░▓▓▓▓▓</pre><p>It&#x2019;s ugly. It doesn&#x2019;t do slanted passages. It&#x2019;s slow. But it worked&#x2026; <img class="smiley" src="http://www.emacswiki.org/pics/dead.png" alt="dead" /></p><p>Perhaps I should just have stuck to the old style:</p><pre class="real">                                   ---------                --------------
                                 ##.&lt;......|                |............|
                                 # |.......|               #-............|
                              ### #........|             ###---------.----
                               #   |.......-#            #           #
                             Y@#   |.......|#          ###         ###
                             #     |.......|#          #           #
                          ..       ---------### -------#         ###
                         --                   # |......#         #
                                              ##......|  ##########
                                                |&gt;....|       --+-.------
                                                |.....|       |.........|
                                                -------       |.........|
                                                              |.........|
                                                              |.........|
                                                              |.........|
                                                              -----------</pre><p>Perhaps what I need is a program that takes a text description of the dungeon and turns it into ASCII art.</p><p>Then again, once we do that, perhaps we might as well do <a class="url http outside" href="http://www.kjd-imc.org/hall-of-fame/setting-design/node-based-megadungeon/">node-based dungeon mapping</a>. I might have to read that series of blog posts by Keith Davies again.</p><p>Then again, I&#x2019;ve just skimmed <a class="url http outside" href="http://inkwellideas.com/advice/random-dungeon-generators-reviewed/">Random Dungeon Generators Reviewed</a> on Inkwell Ideas. Generating good random maps is hard. I still wonder, however. How hard would it be if you provided some input?</p><p>Tags: <a class="outside tag" title="Tag" rel="tag" href="http://alexschroeder.ch/wiki?action=tag;id=RPG">RPG</a> <a class="feed tag" title="Feed for this tag" rel="feed" href="http://alexschroeder.ch/wiki/feed/full/RPG"><img src="http://alexschroeder.ch/pics/rss.png" alt="RSS" /></a></p></div>







